{
    "id": "nouns-grammar",
    "title": "Unit 2 Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass: The Basics of Nouns and Articles",
    "curriculum_id": "unit-2-grammar",
    "voices": {
        "en": "en-AU-WilliamMultilingualNeural",
        "gr": "el-GR-AthinaNeural",
        "gr_en": "en-US-AvaMultilingualNeural"
    },
    "script": [
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Welcome... to the Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass for Unit 2: The Basics of Nouns and Articles. In English... a car is always a car. It doesn't care if it's the subject or the object. But in Greek... nouns are alive. They change their shape... they have genders... and they insist on matching their articles perfectly. Athina... where do we start with these 'living' nouns?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "We start with the 'ID card'. Every Greek noun belongs to one of three categories: Masculine, Feminine, or Neuter. But listen carefully... grammatical gender has nothing to do with being male or female. For example... the word for girl..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "κορίτσι..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "and the word for boy..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "αγόρι..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "are BOTH grammatically neuter!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "That's a huge point. Don't look for logic... look for endings! Athina... what are the typical 'ending signals' for each gender?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "For Masculine... look for"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ος, -ας, ή -ης."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ο φίλος."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "For Feminine... look for"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-α ή -η."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "η αγáπη."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "And for Neuter... look for"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ο, -ι, ή -μα."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "το σπίτι"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "or"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "το μάθημα."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "But wait... I see a 'Warning' in our lesson about the"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ος"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "ending. It's usually masculine... but not always?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Correct. This is why you MUST learn the article first! Some"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ος"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "words are feminine... like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "η οδός,"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "the street. And some are neuter... like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "το λάθος,"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "the mistake. The article"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ο, η, ή το"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "is your only true guide."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So... the 'Golden Rule' is: Never learn a noun without its article. Now... what if we want to say 'a' or 'an'... the indefinite article?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "We have three of those too!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ένας"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for masculine..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "μία"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for feminine... and"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ένα"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for neuter. But here is a native secret: if you see"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "μία"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "written as one syllable..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "μια..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "it's just a quick 'a'. If it's written as"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "μία"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "with an accent... you are emphasizing the number ONE."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Fascinating. Now... let's talk about the 'Shape-Shifting'. The Cases. A noun changes when it moves from being the Subject... to being the Object. In the 'Nominative Case'... the dictionary form... everything is normal. But what happens in the 'Accusative Case', when the noun is the target of the action?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "This is where masculine nouns are very active!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ο πατέρας..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "the father... drops his final"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ς"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "and his article becomes"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "τον."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It becomes..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "τον πατέρα."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Feminine nouns are shy... the noun stays the same... but the article changes from"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "η"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "to"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "την."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "And Neuter nouns? They are perfectly static. They don't change at all!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "το παιδί"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "stays"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "το παιδί."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "But there's a rule about that 'N' in"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "την,"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "isn't there?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Yes! The 'Disappearing Nu'. We keep the"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ν"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "in"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "την"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "only if the next word starts with a vowel or a hard sound like K, P, or T. Otherwise... we drop it. We say"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "τη Δευτέρα..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "but..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "την άνοιξη."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "One more 'Masterclass' secret before we go. In English... we just say 'Maria is here'. But in Greek... that's illegal! You MUST use the article for names. Athina?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ακριβώς!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "We say"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Η Μαρία είναι εδώ."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "'The Maria is here'. Or..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ο Γιώργος."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "'The George'. We even use articles for abstract ideas like 'fear'..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ο φόβος."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So... in Greek... everything needs a handle... an article to carry it. You've now completed the exhaustive dive into Unit 2. You understand gender... you can transform subjects into objects... and you know why Maria is 'The Maria'. Review the family and people vocabulary to practice these rules. Excellent work... and we will see you in Unit 3: Being and Having."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πολύ καλή δουλειά! Τα λέμε στο επόμενο μάθημα."
        }
    ]
}